WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.200
Hello, my name is Camila Saez-Cabezas and I am a scientist in R&D at Dow, where I deliver

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:19.680
analytical solutions using my expertise in measurement science and R programming.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:24.700
Have you ever been eager to jump into a coding project intended to help others, but then

00:00:24.700 --> 00:00:27.740
were disappointed by the development process?

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:33.560
This was me when I first started coding tools for my fellow R&D scientists who are not programmers.

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:35.360
I suspect I'm not alone.

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:38.740
Do you remember what your biggest source of frustration was?

00:00:38.740 --> 00:00:43.540
For me it was the maddening back and forth between feature requests, people changing

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:49.459
their minds about the final product, and rewriting code under a tight deadline in addition to

00:00:49.459 --> 00:00:53.200
unexpected technical challenges.

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:59.180
We can't control the unexpected, however, by controlling our urge to code prematurely,

00:00:59.180 --> 00:01:04.300
we can improve the impact, efficiency, and experience of our development process.

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:10.559
My goal is to share the lessons I've benefited from and convince you to invest time and energy

00:01:10.559 --> 00:01:12.599
into non-coding tasks.

00:01:12.599 --> 00:01:18.360
Don't worry, let's tackle this at the beginning to avoid major course corrections when we're

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:23.440
deeply engaged in coding, demos, deployment, and implementation.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:29.120
I learned to dig deeper during the brainstorming and data inspection phases and gain essential

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:32.879
technical information by playing three roles.

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:38.879
I will demonstrate why using the analytical R&D lab as an example, but I believe this

00:01:38.879 --> 00:01:42.919
approach is useful across many areas and scenarios.

00:01:42.919 --> 00:01:48.260
The mission of analytical scientists in R&D is to problem-solve diverse materials and

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:55.559
complex chemistries by interpreting and combining large volumes of data from different instruments.

00:01:55.559 --> 00:02:00.599
Scientists typically adapt their data workflows to commercial software, not the other way

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:06.139
around, which is why they need your expertise to dream, design, and execute the vision for

00:02:06.139 --> 00:02:07.879
their custom tools.

00:02:07.879 --> 00:02:12.419
Specifically, they need guidance on how to extract more value from their measurement

00:02:12.419 --> 00:02:18.339
data with code and what infrastructure packages and resources suit their needs.

00:02:18.339 --> 00:02:24.619
Let's step away from Posit Workbench temporarily, visit collaborators in their natural habitat,

00:02:24.619 --> 00:02:26.740
and explore together.

00:02:26.740 --> 00:02:29.380
Your first assignment is to be a detective.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:34.479
Shadow your users to discover their sources of pain points and inefficiencies.

00:02:34.479 --> 00:02:39.580
By asking questions as they load samples, run measurements, and analyze data, you will

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:45.679
identify clues and assumptions that are overlooked when these steps are simply described to you.

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:50.220
For example, you notice that your users can export data in a different format that is

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:55.880
easier to parse, or that it's possible to save time and avoid copy-pasting errors by

00:02:55.880 --> 00:03:00.660
extracting instrument metadata from a file otherwise ignored.

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:04.139
Next, be an architect.

00:03:04.139 --> 00:03:08.580
Present your discoveries to the team on the drawing board, help them create the big picture,

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:10.699
and map the path forward.

00:03:10.699 --> 00:03:16.380
Brace yourself to negotiate structural and aesthetic preferences and balance time frame,

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:18.899
cost, and risk constraints.

00:03:18.899 --> 00:03:23.539
Another potential challenge is getting users on board with the solutions they need instead

00:03:23.539 --> 00:03:26.940
of replicating their favorite software features.

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:31.820
Maybe your users are fixated on how they like to edit and annotate graphs in Excel because

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:37.380
they haven't grasped the benefits of reproducible and interactive plots yet.

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:41.539
Maybe you've been tasked with building a web app, but you've identified that what they

00:03:41.539 --> 00:03:44.660
need is an automated and scheduled report.

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:49.580
My point is, here's your chance to pitch your approach and influence the foundation of the

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:52.220
project in a rewarding way.

00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:58.660
Finally, as a chef, choose the perfect ingredients, how to season, and prepare them.

00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:04.300
Think of it as planning ahead for a big demo dinner party and anticipating the right amount

00:04:04.300 --> 00:04:08.139
of food to cook to keep your project on track.

00:04:08.139 --> 00:04:12.820
Imagine people asking, can we test more datasets to increase our confidence?

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:16.019
Did we account for both PDF and CSV files?

00:04:16.019 --> 00:04:20.339
However, it might be too late or tricky to incorporate these changes.

00:04:20.339 --> 00:04:25.380
My intention is not to dismiss the iteration process or testing new ideas as a project

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:26.380
evolves.

00:04:26.380 --> 00:04:32.079
Instead, agreeing on the representative datasets and require performance early will set the

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:36.279
stage for a sweet and satisfying recipe for success.

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:41.559
I hope that I've inspired you to engage with your stakeholders and collaborators as a detective,

00:04:41.559 --> 00:04:43.519
architect, and chef.

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:46.760
Try it for your next project and reach out to discuss more.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:50.839
I love brainstorming in this space, and it's better when we do it together.

00:04:50.839 --> 00:04:51.920
Thank you for listening.

